ution**\\n\\nI'm thinking we shouldn't run tests directly without proper setup. Instead, it might be best to use actual test classes that are already compiled and available on disk. During the JVM agent run, the classpath should include build/classes/java/test. I wonder if setting the java.class.path can help isolate things, so we don’t end up scanning the entire classpath. I’ll look into copying necessary files, but what about native class resources? Maybe I should start with a simple test, like checking if LoadingTestCollector().collectTests() contains the nested classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Debugging loading class issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about loading a class and if it needs to resolve “super org.junit.” If I load with resolve set to false, that could mean not resolving? But then getMethods might need to load supertypes or annotations, which makes me wonder if there’s a NoClassDefFoundError for org/junit/jupiter/api? The isTestClass(String) function seems to catch that error and return false, which could be a good sign.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class coverage options**\\n\\nI'm focused on coverage here, likely relating to the JVM agent rather than being native. It seems like manually writing class bytes might be impossible. Maybe I could embed Base64 of compiled simple classes and include those constants generated from class files. However, the classes would need to be compiled against junit.framework.TestCase for the suite. I think we can create static classes in a test package and obtain the Base64 bytes at patch time. It looks like we might also use javac without running tests.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_OGWevTAuucpoyUZeuCTxDmWh|fc_0ab6febfddb8b3450169f9106dffc881969299a9b89e8d56fa", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/junit/junit/3.7/build/classes/java/test -type f | sort | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input"